### Description

This is an intermittent issue. But I have scenarios where it fails 80% of the time. I think it got a little bit worse when I went from 13.x.x -> 14.x.x. But that might be due to other code changes. 
I don't think I can reproduce it in StackBlitz since it's involved a complex setup and a chain of events.
But I can certainly try if the description is not detailed enough.

When opening dialogs the `afterOpened()` observer is not always "called". And since that's where I run `updateSize()` and `updatePosition()`. The dialog ends up looking like this:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5993909/178484322-8794ebc8-650e-429f-8276-9a00a269dda6.png)

If I run `this.cd.markForCheck()` after the dialog code the observer is called, so it definitely has something to do with Change Detection. However this is a feasible solution since I open the dialogs from a common services, where injecting ChangeDetectionref is not possible.

`this.applicationRef.tick();` does not help (I thought this was a Global Change detection tick?)

The reason I think Change detection is not working properly is because we use native async/await.
However I use the `zone.run()` code for that reason:
```
return this.zone.run(() => {
            const dialog = this.matDialog.open<T>(template, { ...config, viewContainerRef: !useGlobalViewRef ? this.viewContainerRef : undefined });
            dialog.afterOpened().subscribe(() => {
                if (!config.width) {
                    dialog.updateSize();
                }

                if (!config.position) {
                    dialog.updatePosition();
                }
            });
            return dialog;
        });
```

But I still get the issue. This code responsible for calling the `afterOpened` observer is never reached:
```
_containerInstance._animationStateChanged.pipe((0,WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_8__.filter)(event => event.state === 'opened'), (0,WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_9__.take)(1)).subscribe(() => {
      this._afterOpened.next();

      this._afterOpened.complete();
    }); // Dispose overlay when closing animation is complete
```

So the dialog is created, opened and visible on screen. But the `_animationStateChanged` event does not seem to happen, which causes the `afterOpened` observable to never be "called".

Should it be this dependent on Change detection to work? And why does running it in the zone not make the internal `Change Detection` in the `MatDialog` component to work?

Thanks!

### Reproduction

N/A

### Expected Behavior

The `afterOpened()` observer should be "called"

### Actual Behavior

The `afterOpened()` observer is not called due to some animationStateChange not being triggered due to Change Detection issues.

